R Notebook

Cellranger detected ~ 40000 nuclei after analysis, although I had only targeted to recover 6000 nuclei only. As next steps, I sought to understand if empty droplets could be identified based on their proximity to ranked barcodes between 30,000 to 50,000, that are definitely empty.

I am using Seurats pipeline right now since I have to integrate putative empty barcodes as well.

library(Seurat)
library(Matrix)
white_05=Read10X(data.dir = "/home/rstudio/time-series/umi-counts/white_05_inex")
x=as.matrix(colSums(white_05_raw))
y=as.matrix(sort(x = x[,1],decreasing = TRUE))
first_index=15000
last_index=50000
cells=colnames(white_05)
empty=rownames(y)[first_index:last_index]
mat_cells=white_05_raw[,cells]
mat_empty=white_05_raw[,empty]
mat_conc=cbind(mat_cells,mat_empty)
obj=CreateSeuratObject(counts = mat_conc)
Non-unique cell names (colnames) present in the input matrix, making unique
obj@meta.data$annotation=factor("cells",levels = c("cells","empty"))
obj@meta.data[empty,"annotation"]="empty"
# These are now standard steps in the Seurat workflow for visualization and clustering
obj=SetIdent(object = obj,value = "annotation")
obj=NormalizeData(obj)
